01-notes/week-01-summary.md
# Week 1 Summary

## Objective
Build a simple understanding of my home network.

## What I set up
- Created project folders
- Created initial asset inventory
- Created first network diagram

## My current network in plain English
My home network uses a Netgear R7900P router as the main gateway.
Two Linux-based machines are connected via Ethernet: a Linux NUC and an iMac running Debian.
The NUC also hosts Kali VM(s) and some Docker containers.
Other devices connect over Wi-Fi, including a Roku, MacBook, iPhones, and a weather/sprinkler station.

## What I know so far
- Remote management is off
- No manual port forwarding is configured
- UPnP was on earlier and may now be off depending on my change
- No obvious VPN or proxy-sharing software is in use
- Docker exists on one Linux machine

## What I do not know yet
- Exact services running on each Linux host
- Which ports are listening on each Linux machine
- Whether any container is reachable from the LAN
- Normal traffic patterns
- Router log visibility

## Questions for next week
- What services are running on each Linux machine?
- Which ports are open locally?
- Which services are expected vs unexpected?

01-notes/week-01-glossary.md
Very short definitions
LAN: your local home network
WAN: the outside network/internet side
router: device connecting your home network to the internet
gateway: the device your local devices use to reach outside networks
DHCP: gives devices local IP addresses automatically
DNS: turns names like example.com into IP addresses
NAT: lets many home devices share one public internet connection
private IP: internal home-network address
port: numbered entry point used by network services




